Because the original array's elements from n-x to n-x + y-1 are the y elements we need. So their sum is a[n-x + y -1] - a[n-x -1]. But this is only if the group starts at n-x.

But wait, if n-x is 0, then a[n-x-1] would be a[-1], which is invalid. So the code in the else case uses a[n-x + y -1] when y is such that n-x-1 is -1 (i.e., when n-x is 0, x =n). So in that case, the sum is a[n-x + y-1], which is a[y-1], which is the sum of the first y elements. So the code's logic is that for a query (x, y), the answer is either a[...] - a[...] or a[...], depending on whether there's a need to subtract. The code has:

if (condition) {
    cout << a[n-x + y -1] - a[n-x -1] << "\n";
} else {
    cout << a[n-x + y -1] << "\n";
} So the condition is checking whether n-x is zero or not.
